# 1. The CI/CD Pipeline (GitHub Actions)

In the enterprise, code doesn't just run on your desktop. You need to show that your evaluation and safety tests run automatically when someone opens a Pull Request.

Create this file in your repo at `.github/workflows/ci.yml`.

```yaml
name: Multi-Tenant LLM CI/CD

on:
  push:
    branches: [ main ]
  pull_request:
    branches: [ main ]

jobs:
  test-and-eval:
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest
    steps:
      - name: Checkout repository
        uses: actions/checkout@v3

      - name: Set up Python
        uses: actions/setup-python@v4
        with:
          python-version: '3.10'

      - name: Install dependencies
        run: |
          python -m pip install --upgrade pip
          pip install pytest requests pandas scikit-learn
          # We mock the heavy ML libraries for CI speed in this POC
          pip install -r requirements-ci.txt 

      - name: Run Unit Tests
        run: |
          echo "Running unit tests for routing and data pipeline..."
          pytest tests/

      - name: Run Data Quality Checks
        run: |
          echo "Verifying no PII exists in processed datasets..."
          python pipeline/quality_report.py --ci-mode

      - name: Run Safety & Leakage Gates
        run: |
          echo "Executing Red Team and Tenant-Leakage prompts against staging API..."
          # In a real pipeline, this spins up a test container and hits it.
          # python evaluation/safety_test.py

      - name: Model Registry Mock
        if: github.ref == 'refs/heads/main'
        run: |
          echo "Merging adapter weights and pushing to Model Registry..."
          echo "Deploying Canary version to Staging via Kubernetes..."
```

**Why this matters:** Even if the GitHub Action just runs basic Python assertions and prints echoes for the heavy ML stuff (because GitHub runners don't have GPUs), having this YAML file in your repo proves you think like an **MLOps Engineer**, not just a notebook researcher.

